<div id="p-project" class="page active">
<div class="wrap">
  <h2>Projects</h2>

  <!-- Project 1 -->
  <div class="proj-item">
    <div class="proj-hero">
      <div class="proj-hero-info">
        <div class="proj-eyebrow">Stanford University · ME 210</div>
        <div class="proj-name">Autonomous Curling Robot</div>
        <div class="proj-subtitle">DROID — Head-to-head competitive autonomous robot</div>
        <div class="proj-meta">
          <span class="proj-date">Feb 2026 – Mar 2026</span>
          <span class="proj-where">Stanford, CA</span>
        </div>
        <div class="proj-tags">
          <span class="proj-tag">Arduino Mega</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">State Machine</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">IR Sensors</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">Ultrasonic Sensors</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">Servo Motor</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">Mechanical Design</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <img class="proj-hero-img" src="curling robot.jpg" alt="Autonomous Curling Robot">
    </div>

    <div class="proj-sections">
      <div class="proj-section">
        <div class="proj-section-label">Concept</div>
        <div class="proj-section-content">
          Designed and built a fully autonomous robot to compete in a head-to-head curling match on a 16-foot arena within 3 weeks. Starting from a random position, the robot must self-orient, follow a line to the shooting point, launch 8-oz steel pucks into the scoring area, and return to base for reloading — all within a 2-minute time limit and a 13 × 13 in starting footprint.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="proj-section">
        <div class="proj-section-label">Mechanical Design</div>
        <div class="proj-section-content">
          Used ultrasonic sensors for initial orientation and IR sensors for line following and positioning. For shooting, a servo motor pushes the puck down a slide that converts gravitational potential energy into forward speed. An initial flywheel design was tested but removed — the servo-and-slide combination proved sufficient and simpler to tune. To ensure straight launches, the servo was deliberately offset from the central axis to cancel the angular bias introduced by the circular puck storage ring, maximizing momentum transfer while keeping the overall center of mass balanced.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="proj-section">
        <div class="proj-section-label">Algorithm</div>
        <div class="proj-section-content">
          The state machine runs four phases: <strong>(1) Corner alignment</strong> — four ultrasonic sensors (two rear, two left) rotate the robot until both pairs read equal distances, confirming alignment parallel to the walls. <strong>(2) Line acquisition</strong> — the robot advances until a rear IR sensor detects the hogline, then turns right until the front-right IR sensor picks up the center line. <strong>(3) Line following &amp; shooting</strong> — three mid-IR sensors steer the robot (left/right correction or straight), stopping when both front IR sensors detect the shooting line; a 360° servo then dispenses all pucks over 2 seconds. <strong>(4) Return &amp; reload</strong> — the robot reverses along the line, stops when the rear ultrasonic reads under 10 cm, rotates to face the starting zone, and waits 10 seconds before repeating the cycle.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="proj-section">
        <div class="proj-section-label">Result</div>
        <div class="proj-section-content">
          Successfully completed all autonomous tasks — orientation, line following, puck dispensing, and return-to-base — within the 2-minute time limit. <strong>Ranked 5th out of 20 teams</strong> in the final checkoff.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

