  <!-- Project 2 -->
  <div class="proj-item">
    <div class="proj-hero">
      <div class="proj-hero-info">
        <div class="proj-eyebrow">Shanghai Jiao Tong University · Student Innovation Practice Program (IPP28037)</div>
        <div class="proj-name">Saxaul Seedling Auto-Planting Robot</div>
        <div class="proj-subtitle">Autonomous desert reforestation vehicle with hollow-drill seedling mechanism</div>
        <div class="proj-meta">
          <span class="proj-date">Oct 2023 – Sep 2024</span>
          <span class="proj-where">Shanghai, China · Tengger Desert, Gansu</span>
        </div>
        <div class="proj-tags">
          <span class="proj-tag">SolidWorks</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">3D Printing</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">Laser Cutting</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">Arduino</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">Mechanism Design</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">Field Testing</span>
          <span class="proj-tag">Team Lead</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <video class="proj-hero-img" src="Project2whole.mp4" autoplay loop muted playsinline></video>
    </div>

    <div class="proj-sections">
      <div class="proj-section">
        <div class="proj-section-label">Concept</div>
        <div class="proj-section-content">
          Saxaul trees are critical for combating desertification in northwestern China — they anchor soil and support the cultivation of Cistanche, a high-value medicinal crop. However, harsh desert conditions (sandstorms, wild rabbits, gerbil damage) result in low survival rates. This project designed an autonomous solar-powered trolley to patrol a planting base, replant seedlings, and return to charge automatically — enabling unattended, scalable reforestation.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="proj-section">
        <div class="proj-section-label">Design</div>
        <div class="proj-section-content">
          The vehicle integrates three core subsystems. The <strong>seedling warehouse</strong> uses a roller mechanism (stepper motor, 1:380 gear ratio) to dispense one seedling per cycle from a dual-sided acrylic tray. The <strong>transport mechanism</strong> uses a linkage-driven cylindrical tube with a gear-rack opening device and internal spring to orient and deliver the seedling upright to the drill. The <strong>hollow drill</strong> — the core innovation — is a T-thread (pitch 10 mm) alloy screw that rotates into the sand while a fish-line/steel-wire internal mechanism opens the drill tip at depth to deposit the seedling, then retracts to close. The chassis uses four independently driven soft rubber wheels with an Ackermann steering system adapted for loose sand.
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="proj-section">
        <div class="proj-section-label">Result</div>
        <div class="proj-section-content">
          Conducted field testing at the Tengger Desert in Gansu during winter break. Identified and resolved drill penetration issues by adding a ball screw, widening the thread profile, and upgrading to a higher-torque stepper motor. FEA in SolidWorks SimulationXpress confirmed the drill's structural safety factor exceeded 1.19×10⁶. The final prototype successfully completed the full planting cycle: seedling dispensing, upright transport, drill descent, tip opening, seedling deposit, and drill retraction.
          <div class="award">🏆 Top 1% Investment Award — Tencent 'Light' Technology Charity Creation Camp</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

